INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9033e07b-5eaa-4256-8920-1038b71b3e93',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Snyk Semgrep: Crafting Custom Rules with Patterns and CI Integration$escape$,
  $escape$Snyk Semgrep allows you to create custom rules using patterns to detect and fix security vulnerabilities. You can leverage the Semgrep community rules and extend them to fit your project's needs. To integrate custom rules with your CI/CD pipeline, use the Semgrep CLI or API to automate the scanning process. Here's an example of a custom pattern written in Semgrep's Pattern Language:

// @version 1.0
// @description Check for insecure deserialization

match $x := call('org.apache.commons.lang3.SerializationUtils.deserialize', arg(...));
when $x
  -> error('Insecure deserialization detected')


To integrate this rule with your CI pipeline, use the Semgrep CLI with the `--ci` flag:
snyk semgrep --ci -r . --config semgrep.yml

You can also use the Snyk API to trigger Semgrep scans programmatically.$escape$,
  NULL,
  NULL,
